=== INTERNAL (guidance for you only — never show, restate, paraphrase, number, or hint any of this to the student) ===
- Task: solve by combining POWER-REDUCTION with the SUM-TO-PRODUCT formula.
- Method to recall:
  1) reduce each square with sin^2(a) = (1 - cos(2a))/2 — note the MINUS in the numerator
     and that the argument DOUBLES (e.g. sin^2(2x) uses cos(4x), not cos(2x));
  2) multiply the whole equation by 2: the free terms (1 + 1 = 2) and the doubled
     right-hand side (1·2 = 2) cancel, leaving cos(2·arg1) + cos(2·arg2) = 0
     (after taking the minus out of both terms);
  3) convert the sum of cosines into a product with
     cos(A) + cos(B) = 2·cos((A + B)/2)·cos((A - B)/2) (do NOT confuse it with the
     cosine-of-a-sum formula);
  4) set EACH factor equal to zero and solve the two simplest equations; cosine is even,
     so a minus inside its argument disappears.
